 of being recognized. And that could be starting out in the school years, on the schoolyard.

03:53.200 --> 03:56.720
 It could be within their own family, not just in their peer group.

03:56.720 --> 04:03.440
 Those kind of people we often see craving leadership positions from a young age

04:04.160 --> 04:08.880
 often end up in positions of power, but they can be varied positions of power.

04:09.520 --> 04:14.080
 You can have power in an institution where your power is purposefully limited.

04:15.200 --> 04:22.240
 For example, there's a board or a consultative body or a separation of powers. Not everyone craves

04:22.240 --> 04:29.920
 power whereby they're the sole power or their unconstrained power. That's a little bit less

04:29.920 --> 04:37.520
 usual. We may think that everybody does, but not everybody does. Those people who do crave

04:37.520 --> 04:45.920
 that kind of power, unconstrained the ability to decide as much as life or death of other people,

04:45.920 --> 04:53.440
 most people are not everyday people. They're not the people you encounter in your daily life,

04:53.440 --> 04:59.600
 for the most part. Those are extraordinary people. Most of them don't have the opportunity

04:59.600 --> 05:05.280
 to live that dream. Very few of them, in fact, end up with the opportunity to live that dream.

05:05.280 --> 05:10.400
 So percentage wise, in your sense, if we think of George Washington, for example,

05:10.400 --> 05:18.480
 most would most people given the choice of absolute power over a country versus maybe

05:19.280 --> 05:25.280
 the capped power that the United States presidential role, at least at the founding

05:25.280 --> 05:28.640
 of the country, represented, what do you think most people would choose?

05:29.600 --> 05:34.480
 Well, Washington was in a position to exercise far greater power than he did.

05:34.480 --> 05:45.360
 And in fact, he didn't take that option. He was more interested in seeing institutionalization,

05:46.640 --> 05:52.320
 of seeing the country develop strong institutions rather than an individual leader like himself

05:52.320 --> 05:59.200
 have excess power. So that's very important. So like I said, not everyone craves unconstrained

05:59.200 --> 06:04.240
 power even if they're very ambitious. And of course, Washington was very ambitious. He was a

06:04.240 --> 06:11.840
 successful general before he was a president. So that clearly comes from the influences on your

06:11.840 --> 06:18.960
 life, where you grow up, how you grow up, how you raised, what kind of values are imparted to you

06:18.960 --> 06:26.240
 along the way. You can understand power as the ability to share, or you can understand

06:26.240 --> 06:31.920
 or the ability to advance something for the collective in a collective process,

06:31.920 --> 06:36.400
 not an individual process. So power comes in many different varieties.

06:37.680 --> 06:44.480
 And ambition doesn't always equate to despotic power. Despotic power is something

06:45.360 --> 06:53.600
 different from ordinary institutional power that we see. The president of MIT does not have

06:53.600 --> 07:01.760
 unconstrained power. The president of MIT rightly must consult with other members of the administration,

07:01.760 --> 07:07.280
 with the faculty members, to a certain extent with the student body, and certainly with the

07:07.280 --> 07:16.080
 trustees of MIT. Those constraints make the institution strong and enduring and make the

07:16.080 --> 07:22.000
 decisions better than they would be if he had unconstrained power. But you can't say that the

07:22.000 --> 07:29.440
 president is not ambitious. Of course, the president is ambitious. We worry about unconstrained power.

07:29.440 --> 07:35.920
 We worry about executive authority that's not limited. That's the definition of authoritarianism

07:35.920 --> 07:44.240
 or tyranny. Unlimited or barely limited executive authority. Executive authority is necessary to

07:44.240 --> 07:50.160
 carry out many functions. We all understand that. That's why MIT has an executive, has a president.

07:50.160 --> 08:00.640
 But unlimited or largely unconstrained executive power is detrimental to even the person who

08:00.640 --> 08:07.520
 exercises that power. So what do you think? It's an interesting notion. We kind of take it for granted

08:07.520 --> 08:14.560
 that constraints on executive power is a good thing. But why is that necessarily true? So what

08:14.560 --> 08:24.240
 is it about absolute power that does something bad to the human mind? The popular saying of absolute

08:24.240 --> 08:31.920
 power corrupts absolutely. Is that the case? That the power in itself is the thing that

08:32.800 --> 08:37.680
 corrupts the mind in some kind of way where it leads to a bad leadership over time?

08:38.640 --> 08:43.840
 People make more mistakes when they're not challenged, when they don't have to explain

08:43.840 --> 08:51.200
 things and get others to vote and go along with it, when they can make a decision without anybody

08:51.200 --> 08:57.840
 being able to block their decision or to have input necessarily on their decision. You're more

08:57.840 --> 09:05.440
 prone to mistakes. You're more prone to extremism. There's a temptation there. For example, we have

09:05.440 --> 09:14.720
 separation of powers in the United States. The Congress has authority that the president doesn't

09:14.720 --> 09:20.800
 have, as for example, in budgeting the so called power of the purse. This can be very frustrating.

09:21.440 --> 09:26.480
 People want to see things happen, and they complain that there's a do nothing Congress or

09:26.480 --> 09:34.560
 that the situation is stalemated. But actually that's potentially a good thing. In fact, that's

09:34.560 --> 09:41.120
 how our system was designed. Our system was designed to prevent things happening in government.

09:42.320 --> 09:47.600
 There's frustration with that, but ultimately that's the strength of the institutions we have.

09:48.560 --> 09:54.880
 When you see unconstrained executive authority, there can be a lot of dynamism, a lot of things

09:54.880 --> 10:00.800
 can get done quickly, but those things can be like, for example, what happened in China under Mao

10:00.800 --> 10:06.240
 Mao, or what happened in the Soviet Union under Stalin, or what happened in Haiti under

10:06.960 --> 10:13.280
 Papa Doc and then Baby Doc, or fill in the blank. What happens sometimes in corporations where a

10:13.280 --> 10:20.720
 corporate leader is not constrained by the shareholders, by the board, or by anything,

10:21.440 --> 10:25.680
 and they can seem to be a genius for a while, but eventually it catches up to them.

10:25.680 --> 10:32.560
 And so the idea of constraints on executive power is absolutely fundamental to the American

10:32.560 --> 10:40.400
 system, American way of thinking, and not only America, obviously large other parts of the world

10:41.040 --> 10:46.400
 that have a similar system, not an identical system, but a similar system of checks and balances

10:46.400 --> 10:54.160
 on executive power. And so the case that I study, the only checks and balances on executive power

10:54.160 --> 11:02.960
 are circumstantial. So for example, distances in the country, it's hard to do something over 5,000

11:02.960 --> 11:09.360
 miles, or the amount of time in a day, it's hard for a leader to get to every single thing the

11:09.360 --> 11:15.120
 leader wants to get to because there are only 24 hours in a day. Those are circumstantial constraints

11:15.120 --> 11:21.840
 on executive power. They're not institutional constraints on executive power. One of the constraints

11:21.840 --> 11:27.600
 on executive power that the United States has versus Russia, maybe something you've

11:27.600 --> 11:31.840
 implied and actually spoke directly to is there's something in the Russian people and the Soviet

11:31.840 --> 11:39.680
 people that are attracted to authoritarian power, psychologically speaking, or at least the kind

11:39.680 --> 11:48.000
 of leaders that sought authoritarian power throughout its history. And that desire for that

11:48.000 --> 11:53.840
 kind of human is a lack of a constraint. In America, it seems as people we desire

11:55.360 --> 12:00.080
 somebody not like Stalin, somebody more like George Washington. So that's another constraint,

12:00.720 --> 12:05.600
 the belief of the people, what they admire in a leader, what they seek in a leader.

12:06.480 --> 12:14.560
 So maybe you can speak to, well, first of all, can you speak briefly to that psychology of

12:14.560 --> 12:21.280
 is there a difference between the Russian people and the American people in terms of just what we

12:21.280 --> 12:28.960
 find attractive in a leader? Not as great a difference as it might seem. There are, unfortunately,

12:28.960 --> 12:35.920
 many Americans who would be happy with an authoritarian leader in the country. It's

12:35.920 --> 12:42.560
 by no means a majority. It's not even a plurality. But nonetheless, it's a real sentiment in the

12:42.560 --> 12:49.120
 population. Sometimes because they feel frustrated, because things are not getting done. Sometimes

12:49.120 --> 12:55.040
 because they're against something that's happening in the political realm, and they feel it has to

12:55.040 --> 13:01.040
 be corrected and corrected quickly. It's a kind of impulse. People can regret the impulse later

13:01.040 --> 13:08.560
 on that the impulse is motivated by reaction to their environment. In the Russian case, we have

13:08.560 --> 13:15.200
 also people who crave, sometimes known as a strong hand and iron hand and authoritarian leader,

13:15.840 --> 13:22.240
 because they want things to be done and be done more quickly that align with their desires.

13:23.200 --> 13:29.280
 But I'm not sure it's a majority in the country today. Certainly in Stalin's time,

13:30.080 --> 13:36.080
 this was a widespread sentiment, and people had few alternatives that they understood or could

13:36.080 --> 13:43.360
 appeal to. Nowadays, in the globalized world, the citizens of Russia can see how other systems have

13:43.360 --> 13:49.200
 constraints on executive power, and the life isn't so bad there. In fact, the life might even be

13:49.200 --> 13:58.880
 better. So the impatience, the impulsive quality, the frustration does sometimes, and people reinforce

13:58.880 --> 14:06.240
 their craving for the unconstrained executive to, quote, get things done or shake things up or

14:07.120 --> 14:13.440
 yes, that's true. But in the Russian case, I'm not sure it's cultural today. I think it might be more

14:14.320 --> 14:22.320
 having to do with the failures, the functional failures of the kind of political system that

14:22.320 --> 14:31.280
 they tried to institute after the Soviet collapse. And so it may be frustration with the version of

14:31.280 --> 14:36.800
 constraints on executive power they got and how it didn't work the way it was imagined,

14:37.760 --> 14:47.040
 which has led to a sense in which non constrained executive power could fix things. But I'm not

14:47.040 --> 14:52.400
 sure that that's a majority sentiment in the Russian case, although it's hard to measure because

14:52.400 --> 15:01.120
 under authoritarian regimes, a public opinion is shaped by the environment in which people live,

15:01.120 --> 15:08.320
 which is very constrained in terms of public opinion. But on that point, why, at least from a

15:08.320 --> 15:13.200
 distance, does there seem to nevertheless be support for the current Russian president,

15:13.200 --> 15:21.680
 Vladimir Putin? Is that have to do with the fact that measuring, getting good metrics and

15:21.680 --> 15:27.440
 statistics on support is difficult in authoritarian governments? Or is there still something appealing

15:28.000 --> 15:33.840
 to that kind of power to the people? I think we have to give credit to President Putin for

15:33.840 --> 15:42.480
 understanding the psychology of the Russians who to whom he appeals. Many of them were the

15:42.480 --> 15:49.440
 losers in the transition from communism. They were the ones whose pensions were destroyed by

15:49.440 --> 15:55.680
 inflation or whose salaries didn't go up or whose regions were abandoned. They were not

15:55.680 --> 16:01.280
 the winners for the most part. And so I think there's an understanding on his part of their

16:01.280 --> 16:06.960
 psychology. Putin has grown in the position. He was not a public politician when he first started

16:06.960 --> 16:13.120
 out. He was quite poor in public settings. He didn't have the kind of political instincts

16:13.120 --> 16:18.960
 that he has now. He didn't have the appeal to traditional values and the Orthodox Church and

16:18.960 --> 16:28.560
 some of the other dimensions of his rule today. So yes, we have to give some credit to Putin himself

16:28.560 --> 16:35.120
 for this, in addition to the frustrations and the mass of the people. But let's think about it

16:35.120 --> 16:41.280
 this way, in addition, without taking away the fact that he's become a better retail politician

16:41.280 --> 16:47.920
 over time and that sentiment has shifted because of the disappointments with the transition with

16:47.920 --> 17:00.240
 the population. When I ask my kids, am I a good dad? My kids don't have any other dad to measure me

17:00.240 --> 17:08.800
 against. I'm the only dad they know and I'm the only dad they can choose or not choose. If they

17:08.800 --> 17:17.920
 don't choose me, they still get me as dad. So with Putin today, he's the only dad that the Russian

17:17.920 --> 17:24.000
 people have. Now, if my kids were introduced to alternative fathers, they might be better than

17:24.000 --> 17:32.800
 me. They might be more loving, more giving, funnier, richer, whatever it might be, they might be more

17:32.800 --> 17:38.960
 appealing. There are some blood ties there, for sure, that I have with my kids, but they would at

17:38.960 --> 17:47.200
 least be able to choose alternatives and then I would have to win their favor in that constellation

17:47.200 --> 17:53.120
 of alternatives. If President Putin were up against real alternatives, if the population

17:53.120 --> 18:00.160
 had real choice and that choice could express itself and have resources and have media and

18:00.160 --> 18:07.680
 everything else the way he does, maybe he would be very popular and maybe his popularity would not

18:07.680 --> 18:15.600
 be as great as it currently is. So the absence of alternatives is another factor that reinforces

18:15.600 --> 18:22.320
 his authority and his popularity. Having said that, there are many authoritarian leaders

18:23.040 --> 18:30.720
 who deny any alternatives to the population and are not very popular. So denial of alternatives

18:30.720 --> 18:36.800
 doesn't guarantee you the popularity. You still have to figure out the mass psychology and be able

18:36.800 --> 18:47.200
 to appeal to it. In the Russian case, the winners from the transition live primarily in the big

18:47.200 --> 18:59.040
 cities and are self employed or entrepreneurial. Even if they're not self employed, they're able

18:59.040 --> 19:07.040
 to change careers. They have tremendous skills and talent and education and knowledge, as well as

19:07.760 --> 19:14.480
 these entrepreneurial or dynamic personalities. Putin also appealed to them. He did that with

19:14.480 --> 19:23.360
 Medvedev and it was a very clever ruse. He himself appealed to the losers from the transition,

19:23.360 --> 19:32.480
 the small towns, the rural, the people who were not well off, and he had them for the most part.

19:32.480 --> 19:37.040
 Not all. We don't want to generalize to say that he had every one of them because those people have

19:37.040 --> 19:43.360
 views of their own, sometimes in contradiction with the president of Russia. And then he appealed

19:43.360 --> 19:49.840
 to the opposite people, the successful urban base through the so called reformer Medvedev,

19:49.840 --> 19:56.720
 the new generation, the technically literate prime minister who for a time was president.

19:56.720 --> 20:03.600
 And so that worked very successfully for Putin. He was able to bridge a big divide in the society

20:03.600 --> 20:10.480
 and gain a greater mass support than he would otherwise have had by himself. That ruse only

20:10.480 --> 20:19.280
 worked through the time that Medvedev was temporarily president for a few years because of

20:19.280 --> 20:26.080
 the constitution Putin couldn't do three consecutive terms and stepped aside in what they call

20:26.080 --> 20:35.920
 castling in chess. When this was over, Putin had difficulty with his popularity. There were mass

20:35.920 --> 20:43.120
 protests in the urban areas. Precisely that group of the population that he had been able to win in

20:43.120 --> 20:52.640
 part because of the Medvedev castling and now had had their delusions exposed and were disillusioned.

20:53.840 --> 20:58.160
 And there were these mass protests in the urban areas, not just in the capital, by the way,

20:58.800 --> 21:04.160
 and Putin had to, as it were, come up with a new way to fix his popularity, which happened to be

21:04.160 --> 21:13.920
 the annexation of Crimea, from which he got a very significant bump. However, the trend is back

21:13.920 --> 21:20.240
 in the other direction. It's diminishing again, although it's still high relative to other leaders

21:20.240 --> 21:28.720
 around the world. So I wouldn't say that he's unpopular with mass in Russia. There is some

21:28.720 --> 21:34.320
 popularity there. There is some success. But I would say it's tough for us to gauge because of

21:34.320 --> 21:40.320
 the lack of alternatives. And Putin is unpopular inside the state administration.

21:42.080 --> 21:47.920
 At every level, the bureaucracy of leadership. Because those people are well informed and they

21:47.920 --> 21:53.920
 understand that the country is declining, that the human capital is declining, the infrastructure

21:53.920 --> 21:59.680
 is declining, the economy is not really growing. It's not really diversifying. Russia is not

21:59.680 --> 22:05.280
 investing in its future. The state officials understand all of that. And then they see that

22:05.280 --> 22:13.040
 the Putin clique is stealing everything in sight. So between the failure to invest in a future

22:14.000 --> 22:19.680
 and the corruption of a narrow group around the president, there's disillusionment in the state

22:19.680 --> 22:26.160
 apparatus because they see this more clearly or more closely than the mass of the population.

22:27.280 --> 22:37.840
 They can't necessarily yet oppose this in public because there are people, they have families,

22:37.840 --> 22:43.520
 they have careers, they have children who want to go to school or want a job. And so there are

22:43.520 --> 22:50.720
 constraints on their ability to oppose the regime based upon what we might call cowardice or other

22:50.720 --> 22:57.840
 people might call realism. I don't know how courageous people can be when their family,

22:57.840 --> 23:05.200
 children, career are on the line. So it's very interesting dynamic to see the disillusionment

23:05.200 --> 23:11.280
 inside the government with the president, which is not yet fully public for the most part,

23:11.280 --> 23:16.640
 but could become public. And once again, if there's an alternative, if an alternative appears,

23:16.640 --> 23:21.040
 things could shift quickly. And that alternative could come from inside the regime.

23:21.920 --> 23:28.960
 From inside the regime. But the leadership, the party, the people that are now, as you're saying,

23:28.960 --> 23:35.360
 opposed to Putin, nevertheless, maybe you can correct me, but it feels like there's

23:35.360 --> 23:42.080
 just structurally is deeply corrupt. So each of each of the people we're talking about are

23:43.840 --> 23:50.000
 don't feel like a George Washington. Once again, the circumstances don't permit them

23:50.000 --> 23:56.480
 to act that way necessarily, right? George Washington did great things, but in certain

23:56.480 --> 24:03.440
 circumstances, a lot of the state officials in Russia, for certain, are corrupt. There's no

24:03.440 --> 24:12.160
 question. Many of them, however, are patriotic. And many of them feel badly about where the

24:12.160 --> 24:17.760
 country has been going. They would prefer that the country was less corrupt. They would prefer

24:17.760 --> 24:24.800
 that there were greater investment in all sorts of areas of Russia. They might even,

24:24.800 --> 24:31.120
 themselves, steal less if they could be guaranteed that everybody else would steal less.

24:31.120 --> 24:39.280
 There's a deep and abiding patriotism inside Russia, as well as inside the Russian regime.

24:40.400 --> 24:46.080
 So they understand that Putin, in many ways, rescued the Russian state from the chaos of the

24:46.080 --> 24:54.880
 1990s. They understand that Russia was in very bad shape as an incoherent failing state almost

24:54.880 --> 25:03.120
 when Putin took over, and that he did some important things for Russia's stability and

25:03.120 --> 25:12.720
 consolidation. There's also some appreciation that Putin stood up to the West and stood up to

25:12.720 --> 25:19.440
 more powerful countries and regained a sense of pride and maneuverability for Russia and the

25:19.440 --> 25:26.160
 international system. People appreciate that, and it's real. It's not imagined that Putin accomplished

25:26.160 --> 25:33.840
 that. The problem is the methods that he accomplished it with. He used the kind of methods,

25:33.840 --> 25:40.000
 that is to say, taking other people's property, putting other people in jail for political reasons.

25:40.560 --> 25:45.280
 He used the kind of methods that are not conducive to long term growth and stability.

25:45.280 --> 25:51.840
 So he fixed the problem, but he fixed the problem and then created even bigger long term problems

25:51.840 --> 26:00.320
 potentially. Moreover, all authoritarian regimes that use those methods are tempted to keep using

26:00.320 --> 26:06.400
 them and using them and using them until they're the only ones who are the beneficiaries. The group

26:06.400 --> 26:14.000
 narrows and narrows. The elite gets smaller and narrower. The interest groups get excluded from

26:14.000 --> 26:22.320
 power and their ability to continue enjoying the fruits of the system, and the resentment grows.

26:22.320 --> 26:29.040
 And so that's the situation we have. And Russia is a place that is stuck. It was, to a certain

26:29.040 --> 26:36.800
 extent, rescued. It was rescued with methods that were not conducive to long term success and

26:36.800 --> 26:43.440
 stability. The rescue we're referring to is the economic growth when Putin first took office.

26:43.440 --> 26:48.080
 They had 10 years. They had a full decade of an average of 7% growth a year,

26:48.960 --> 26:55.680
 which was phenomenal and is not attributable predominantly to oil prices. During President

26:55.680 --> 27:03.920
 Putin's first term as president, the average price of oil was $35 a barrel. During his second term

27:03.920 --> 27:12.320
 as president, the average price was $70 a barrel. So during those two terms, when Russia was growing

27:12.320 --> 27:20.720
 at about 7% a year, oil prices were averaging somewhere around $50 a barrel, which is fine,

27:21.280 --> 27:30.000
 but is not the reason because later on, when oil prices were over $100 a barrel, Russia stagnated.

27:30.640 --> 27:34.160
 So the initial growth, do you think Putin deserves some credit for that?

27:34.160 --> 27:41.200
 Yes, he does because he introduced some important liberalizing measures. He lowered taxes.

27:41.200 --> 27:49.200
 He allowed land to be bought and sold. He deregulated many areas of the economy.

27:50.080 --> 27:57.600
 And so there was a kind of entrepreneurial burst that was partly attributable, partly

27:57.600 --> 28:03.920
 attributable to government policy during his first term. But also he was consolidating political

28:03.920 --> 28:12.480
 power. And as I said, the methods he used overall for the long term, we're not able to continue

28:12.480 --> 28:18.960
 sustain that success. In addition, we have to remember that China played a really big role

28:20.080 --> 28:24.880
 in the success of Russia in the first two terms of Putin's presidency,

28:24.880 --> 28:34.080
 because China's phenomenal growth created insatiable demand for just about everything

28:34.080 --> 28:40.560
 that the Soviet Union used to produce. So fertilizers, cement, fill in the blank,

28:41.520 --> 28:49.360
 chemicals, metals. China had insatiable demand for everything the Soviet Union once produced.

28:49.360 --> 29:00.640
 And so China's raising of global demand overall brought Soviet era industry back from the dead.

29:01.920 --> 29:07.840
 And so there was something that happened. Soviet era industry fell off a cliff in the 1990s.

29:08.720 --> 29:14.720
 There was a decline in manufacturing and industrial production greater than in the Great Depression

29:14.720 --> 29:22.720
 in the US. But a lot of that came back online in the 2000s. And that had to do with China's

29:22.720 --> 29:28.960
 phenomenal growth. The trade between China and Russia was not always direct. So this was an

29:28.960 --> 29:36.880
 indirect effect. But raising global prices for the commodities and the products, the kind of

29:36.880 --> 29:45.040
 lower and lower value products in manufacturing, not high end stuff, but lower end stuff like steel

29:45.040 --> 29:53.520
 or iron or cement or fertilizer, where the value added is not spectacular, but nonetheless,

29:53.520 --> 30:00.400
 which had been destroyed by the 1990s and after the Soviet collapse. This was brought back to life.

30:00.400 --> 30:05.680
 Now you can do that once. You can bring Soviet era industry back to life once.

30:05.680 --> 30:11.440
 And that happened during Putin's first two terms in addition to the liberalizing policies,

30:12.320 --> 30:19.840
 which spurred entrepreneurialism in some small and medium business. The crash of the ruble in 1998,

30:20.400 --> 30:26.000
 which made Russian products much cheaper abroad and made imports much more expensive,

30:26.960 --> 30:34.480
 also facilitated the resuscitation, the revival of domestic manufacturing. So all of this came

30:34.480 --> 30:44.720
 together for that spectacular 10 year, 7% on average economic growth. And moreover, people's

30:44.720 --> 30:53.520
 wages after inflation, their disposable income grew more even than GDP grew. So disposable

30:53.520 --> 31:00.080
 income after inflation, that is a real income, was growing greater than 7%. In some cases,

31:00.080 --> 31:06.240
 10% a year. So there was a boom and the Russian people felt it and it happened during Putin's

31:06.240 --> 31:14.640
 first two terms and people were grateful, rightly so for that. And those who don't want to give Putin

31:14.640 --> 31:23.360
 credit, give oil prices all the credit. But I don't think that oil prices can explain this.

31:23.360 --> 31:28.000
 Having said that, that doesn't mean that this was sustainable over the long term.

31:28.000 --> 31:36.480
 Right. So you've briefly mentioned sort of implying the possibility Stalin held power for,

31:36.480 --> 31:43.760
 let's say, 30 years. You've briefly mentioned that as a question, will Putin be able to beat

31:43.760 --> 31:50.720
 that record, to beat that? So can you talk about your sense of, is it possible that Putin holds

31:50.720 --> 32:00.240
 power for that kind of duration? Let's hope not. Let's hope not for Russia's sake. The primary

32:00.240 --> 32:08.000
 victims of President Putin's power are Russians. They're not Ukrainians, although to a certain

32:08.000 --> 32:14.960
 extent Ukraine has suffered because of Putin's actions. And they're not Americans. They're Russians.

32:14.960 --> 32:21.600
 Moreover, Russia has lost a great deal of human talent. Millions and millions of people have left

32:21.600 --> 32:29.840
 Russia since 1991 overall, somewhere between five and 10 million people have left the country

32:30.880 --> 32:37.200
 and are beyond the borders of the former Soviet Union. So they left the Soviet space entirely.

32:37.760 --> 32:42.560
 Moreover, the people who left are not the poor people. They're not the uneducated.

32:42.560 --> 32:48.640
 They're not the losers. The people who've left are the more dynamic parts of the population,

32:48.640 --> 32:55.360
 the better educated, the more entrepreneurial. So that human capital loss that Russia has suffered

32:55.360 --> 33:02.960
 is phenomenal. And in fact, right here where we're sitting at MIT, we have examples of people who

33:02.960 --> 33:08.800
 are qualified, good enough for MIT, and have left Russia to come to MIT.

33:08.800 --> 33:14.240
 You're looking at one of them. And the other aspect, just to quickly comment,

33:14.240 --> 33:19.200
 is those same people like me. I'm not welcome back.

33:19.200 --> 33:25.200
 No, you're not under the current regime. It was a big loss for Russia if you're patriotic,

33:25.200 --> 33:31.600
 but not from the point of view of the Putin regime. That has to do also factors into popularity.

33:31.600 --> 33:38.320
 If the people who don't like you leave, they're not there to complain, to protest, to vote against

33:38.320 --> 33:46.480
 you. And so your opposition declines when you let them leave. However, it's very costly in human

33:46.480 --> 33:53.840
 capital terms. Hemorrhaging that much human capital is damaging, it's self damaging. And we've seen

33:53.840 --> 33:59.840
 it accelerate. It was already high, but we've seen it accelerate in the last

33:59.840 --> 34:09.520
 in the last seven to eight years of President Putin's rule. And those people are not going

34:09.520 --> 34:14.480
 back of their own volition, but even if they wanted to go back, as you just said, they'd be

34:14.480 --> 34:21.520
 unwelcome. That's a big cost to pay for this regime. And so whatever benefits this regime might or

34:21.520 --> 34:28.880
 might not have given to the country, the disadvantages, the downside, the costs are also

34:28.880 --> 34:35.280
 really high. So we don't want Putin lasting in power as long as Stalin. It would be better

34:35.840 --> 34:41.600
 if Russia were able to choose among options, to choose a new leader among options.

34:42.640 --> 34:49.040
 Many people speculate that President Putin will name a successor the way Yeltsin named Putin as

34:49.040 --> 34:56.000
 his successor, Boris, President Boris Yeltsin. And then Putin will leave the stage and allow

34:56.000 --> 35:03.760
 the successor to take over. That might seem like a good solution. But once again, we don't need a

35:03.760 --> 35:09.680
 system where you hang on for as long as possible than to nominate who's going to take over. We

35:09.680 --> 35:17.760
 need a system that has the kind of corrective mechanisms that democracies and markets have,

35:17.760 --> 35:24.320
 along with rule of law. A corrective mechanism is really important because all leaders make mistakes.

35:24.320 --> 35:32.400
 But when you can't correct for the mistakes, then the mistakes get compounded. Putin could

35:32.400 --> 35:39.440
 well he seems to be healthy. He could well last as many years as Stalin. It's hard to predict because

35:39.440 --> 35:47.280
 events intercede sometimes and create circumstances that are unforeseen and leaders get overthrown

35:47.280 --> 35:54.880
 or have a heart attack or whatever. There's a palace insurrection where ambitious leaders on

35:54.880 --> 36:02.560
 the inside, for both personal power and patriotic reasons, try to push aside an aging leader.

36:03.200 --> 36:09.520
 There are many scenarios in which Putin could not last that long. But unfortunately, right now,

36:10.480 --> 36:16.400
 you could also imagine potentially him lasting that long, which as I said, is not an outcome

36:16.400 --> 36:21.840
 if you're patriotic about Russia. It's not an outcome you would wish out to the country.

36:21.840 --> 36:30.240
 I guess a very difficult question. But what practically do you feel is a way out of the Putin

36:30.240 --> 36:39.920
 regime? Is the way out of the corruption that's deeply underlies the state? If you look from a

36:39.920 --> 36:51.360
 history perspective, is a revolution required? Is violence required? Is from violence within

36:51.360 --> 37:04.560
 or external to the country? Is a powerful, inspiring leader enough to step in and bring

37:04.560 --> 37:11.280
 democracy and the free world to Russia? Russia is not a failed country. It's a

37:11.280 --> 37:19.040
 middle income country with tremendous potential and has proven many times in the past that when

37:19.040 --> 37:27.840
 it gets in a bad way, it can reverse its trajectory. Moreover, violence is rarely ever a solution.

37:27.840 --> 37:35.040
 Violence rarely, it may break an existing trend, but it's rare that violence produces a nonviolent

37:35.040 --> 37:42.400
 sustainable positive outcome. It happens, but it doesn't happen frequently. Societal upheaval

37:44.320 --> 37:52.320
 is not a way always to institutionalize a better path forward because you need institutions. People

37:52.320 --> 37:58.560
 can protest as they did throughout the Middle East and the protests didn't necessarily lead

37:58.560 --> 38:07.360
 to better systems because the step from protest to new, strong, consolidated institutions is a

38:07.360 --> 38:14.240
 colossal leap, not a small step. What we need and what we see from history and situations like this

38:14.240 --> 38:22.560
 is a group within the power structures, which is a patriotic, that sees things going down,

38:22.560 --> 38:30.640
 that is to say, that sees things not developing relative to neighbors, relative to richer countries,

38:30.640 --> 38:37.600
 relative to more successful countries. They want to change the trajectory of Russia.

38:37.600 --> 38:47.920
 And if they can, in a coalition fashion, unseat the current regime for a new power sharing arrangement,

38:48.720 --> 38:53.680
 which once again can be frustrating because you can't do changes immediately,

38:53.680 --> 38:59.840
 you can't do things overnight, but that's the point. Constraints on your ability to change

38:59.840 --> 39:05.440
 everything immediately and to force change overnight is what leads to long term success.

39:05.440 --> 39:16.320
 That's the sustainability of change. So Russia needs stronger institutions. It needs court system

39:17.600 --> 39:24.400
 as well as democratic institutions. It needs functioning open dynamic markets rather than

39:24.400 --> 39:33.120
 monopolies. It needs meritocracy and banks to award loans on the basis of business plans,

39:33.120 --> 39:38.720
 not on the basis of political criteria or corrupt bribery or whatever it might be.

39:39.760 --> 39:47.600
 So Russia needs those kind of functioning institutions that take time, are sometimes slow,

39:48.320 --> 39:55.920
 don't lead to revolutionary transformation, but lead to potentially long term sustainable growth

39:55.920 --> 40:02.320
 without upheaval, without violence, without getting into a situation where all of a sudden

40:02.320 --> 40:09.600
 you need a miracle again. Every time Russia seems to need a miracle, and that's the problem,

40:10.480 --> 40:17.040
 the solution would be not needing a miracle. Now, having said that, the potential is there.

40:17.760 --> 40:25.120
 The civilization that we call Russia is amazingly impressive. It has delivered world class culture,

40:25.120 --> 40:32.960
 world class science. It's a great power. It's not a great power with a strong base right now,

40:32.960 --> 40:38.400
 but nonetheless, it is a great power as it acts in the world. So I wouldn't underestimate Russia's

40:38.400 --> 40:44.560
 abilities here, and I wouldn't write off Russia. I don't see it under the current regime, a renewal

40:44.560 --> 40:52.080
 of the country. But if we can have from within the regime an evolution rather than a revolution

40:52.080 --> 41:00.880
 in a positive direction, and maybe get a George Washington figure who is strong enough to push

41:00.880 --> 41:08.880
 through institutionalization rather than personalism. So if I could ask about one particular individual,

41:10.080 --> 41:14.560
 it'd be just interesting to get your comment, but also as a representative of potential leaders.

41:14.560 --> 41:20.560
 I just on this podcast talked to Gary Kasparov, who I'm not sure if you're familiar with his

41:20.560 --> 41:28.400
 ongoings. So besides being a world class chess player, he's also a very outspoken activist,

41:28.400 --> 41:36.640
 sort of seeing Putin, truly seeing Putin as an enemy of the free world of democracy, of

41:37.840 --> 41:44.400
 balanced government in Russia. What do you think of people like him specifically, or just people

41:44.400 --> 41:53.600
 like him trying as leaders to step in to run for president to symbolize a new chapter in Russia's

41:53.600 --> 42:01.680
 future? So we don't need individuals. Some individuals are very impressive, and they have

42:01.680 --> 42:09.200
 courage, and they protest, and they criticize, and they organize. We need institutions. We need a

42:09.200 --> 42:16.000
 duma or a parliament that functions. We need a court system that functions. That is to say where

42:16.000 --> 42:25.520
 there are a separation of powers, impartial professional civil service, impartial professional

42:26.320 --> 42:32.720
 judiciary. Those are the things Russia needs. It's rare that you get that from an individual,

42:32.720 --> 42:39.440
 no matter how impressive. We had Andrei Sakharov, who was an extraordinary individual,

42:40.560 --> 42:47.920
 who developed the hydrogen bomb under Soviet regime, was a world class physicist,

42:48.960 --> 42:56.400
 was then upset about how his scientific knowledge and scientific achievements were being put to use

42:56.400 --> 43:04.560
 and rebelled to try to put limits, constraints, civilizing humane limits

43:04.560 --> 43:11.760
 and constraints on some of the implications of his extraordinary science. But Sakharov,

43:11.760 --> 43:18.080
 even if he had become the leader of the country, which he did not become, he was more of a moral

43:18.080 --> 43:23.280
 or spiritual leader, it still wouldn't have given you a judiciary. It still wouldn't have

43:23.280 --> 43:28.160
 given you a civil service. It still wouldn't have given you a duma or functioning parliament.

43:28.880 --> 43:34.240
 You need a leader in coalition with other leaders. You need a bunch of leaders,

43:35.760 --> 43:41.120
 a whole group, and they have to be divided a little bit so that not one of them can destroy

43:41.120 --> 43:50.000
 all the others. And they have to be interested in creating institutions, not solely or predominantly

43:50.000 --> 43:57.360
 in their personal power. And so I have no objection to outstanding individuals and to the work that

43:57.360 --> 44:04.000
 they do. But I think in institutional terms, and they need to think that way too in order to be

44:04.000 --> 44:10.640
 successful. So if we go back to the echoes of that after the Russian Revolution with Stalin,

44:10.640 --> 44:17.040
 with Lenin and Stalin, maybe you can correct me, but there was a group of people there

44:17.040 --> 44:28.480
 in that same kind of way, looking to establish institutions that were built in a beautifully

44:28.480 --> 44:37.440
 built around an ideology that they believed is good for the world. So sort of echoing that idea

44:37.440 --> 44:44.160
 of what we're talking about, what Russia needs now, can you, first of all, you've described a

44:44.160 --> 44:51.520
 fascinating thought which is Stalin is having amassed arguably more power than any man in history.

44:52.560 --> 44:58.080
 It's an interesting thing to think about. But can you tell about his journey to getting that power

44:58.080 --> 45:05.520
 after the Russian Revolution? How does that perhaps echo to our current discussion about

45:05.520 --> 45:13.360
 institutions and so on? And just in general, the story I think is fascinating of how one man is

45:13.360 --> 45:21.120
 able to get more power than any other man in history. It is a great story, not necessarily

45:21.120 --> 45:26.640
 from a moral point of view. But if you're interested in power, for sure, it's an incredible story.

45:28.160 --> 45:32.480
 So we have to remember that Stalin is also a product of circumstances,

45:33.360 --> 45:40.480
 not solely his own individual drive, which is very strong. But for example, World War One

45:40.480 --> 45:49.280
 breaks the Tsarist regime, the Tsarist order, imperial Russian state. Stalin has no participation

45:49.280 --> 45:57.040
 whatsoever in World War One. He spends World War One in exile in Siberia. Until the downfall

45:57.760 --> 46:08.240
 of the Tsarist autocracy in February 1917, Stalin is in Eastern Siberian exile. He's only able to

46:08.240 --> 46:16.560
 leave Eastern Siberia when that regime falls. He never fights in the war. He's called up briefly

46:16.560 --> 46:23.360
 towards the end of the war and is disqualified on physical grounds because of physical deformities

46:23.360 --> 46:30.640
 from being drafted. The war continues after the Tsarist regime has been toppled

46:30.640 --> 46:39.280
 in the capital and there's been a revolution. The war continues and that war is very radicalizing.

46:40.480 --> 46:47.360
 The peasants begin to seize the land after the Tsar falls, essentially destroying much of the

46:47.360 --> 46:52.080
 gentry class. Stalin has nothing to do with that. The peasants have their own revolution,

46:52.080 --> 47:00.320
 seizing the land, not in law, but in fact, de facto, not de jure land ownership. So there are

47:00.320 --> 47:09.360
 these really large processes underway that Stalin is alive during, but not a driver of.

47:10.720 --> 47:17.440
 The most improbable thing happens, which is a very small group of people around the figure of

47:17.440 --> 47:26.560
 Vladimir Lenin announces that it has seized power. Now, by this time in October 1917,

47:27.680 --> 47:32.080
 the government that has replaced the Tsar, the so called provisional government,

47:32.080 --> 47:38.320
 has failed. And so there's not so much power to seize from the provisional government.

47:38.320 --> 47:48.400
 What Lenin does is he does a coup on the left. That is to say, Soviets or councils as we would

47:48.400 --> 47:54.400
 call them in English, which represent people's power or the masses participating in politics,

47:54.400 --> 48:00.800
 a kind of radical grassroots democracy, are extremely popular all over the country and

48:00.800 --> 48:09.680
 not dominated by any one group, but predominantly socialist or predominantly leftist. Russia has

48:09.680 --> 48:16.560
 an election during the war, a free and fair election for the most part, despite the war

48:17.360 --> 48:25.440
 at the end of 1917 in December 1917. And three quarters plus of the country votes socialist

48:25.440 --> 48:32.160
 in some form or another. So the battle was over the definition of socialism and who had the right

48:32.800 --> 48:38.480
 to participate in defining socialism, not only what it would be, but who had the right to decide.

48:39.200 --> 48:45.680
 So there's a coup by Lenin's group known as the Bolsheviks against all the other socialists.

48:47.120 --> 48:52.800
 And so Lenin declares a seizure of power whereby the old government has failed,

48:52.800 --> 49:00.080
 people's power, the councils, known as the Soviets, are going to take their place. And Lenin seizes

49:00.080 --> 49:06.560
 power in the name of the Soviets. So it's a coup against the left, against the rest of the left,

49:07.120 --> 49:11.440
 not against the provisional government that has replaced the czar, which has already failed.

49:12.320 --> 49:21.520
 And so Stalin is able to come to power along with Lenin in this crazy seizure of power on the

49:21.520 --> 49:28.000
 left against the rest of the left in October 1917, which we know is the October Revolution.

49:28.000 --> 49:36.000
 And I call the October coup as many other historians call. The October Revolution happened

49:36.000 --> 49:42.000
 after the seizure of power. What's interesting about this episode is that the leftists who seize

49:42.000 --> 49:47.440
 power in the name of the Soviets, in the name of the masses, in the name of people's power,

49:47.440 --> 49:54.880
 they retain their hold. Many times in history, there's a seizure of power by the left,

49:54.880 --> 50:01.600
 and they fail. They collapse. They're cleaned out by an army or what we call forces of order

50:02.320 --> 50:10.240
 by counterrevolutionary forces. Lenin's revolution, Lenin's coup, is successful. It is able to hold

50:10.240 --> 50:18.080
 power and not just seize power. They win a civil war and they're entrenched in the heart of the

50:18.080 --> 50:27.520
 country already by 1921. Stalin is part of that group. Lenin needs somebody to run this new regime

50:27.520 --> 50:33.520
 in the kind of nitty gritty way. Lenin is the leader, the undisputed leader in the Bolshevik

50:33.520 --> 50:42.160
 Party, which changes their name to communists in 1918. He makes Stalin the general secretary

50:42.720 --> 50:49.040
 of the Communist Party. He creates a new position, which hadn't existed before,

50:49.680 --> 50:56.880
 a kind of day to day political manager, a right hand man. Not because Lenin is looking to replace

50:56.880 --> 51:03.040
 himself. He's looking to institutionalize a helpmate, a right hand man. He does this in

51:03.040 --> 51:11.600
 the spring of 1922. Stalin is named to this position, which Lenin has created expressly for

51:11.600 --> 51:18.880
 Stalin. So there's been a coup on the left, whereby the Bolsheviks, who become communists,

51:18.880 --> 51:24.320
 have seized power against the rest of the socialists and anarchists and the entire left.

51:25.280 --> 51:30.160
 And then there's an institutionalization of a position known as general secretary of the

51:30.160 --> 51:36.640
 Communist Party, right hand man of Lenin. Less than six weeks after Lenin has created

51:36.640 --> 51:47.280
 this position and installed Stalin, Lenin has a stroke, a major stroke, and never really returns

51:47.280 --> 51:55.920
 as a full actor to power before he dies of a fourth stroke in January 1924. So a position is

51:55.920 --> 52:03.840
 created for Stalin to run things on Lenin's behalf, and then Lenin has a stroke. And so Stalin now

52:03.840 --> 52:10.960
 has this new position, general secretary, but he's the right hand of a person who's no longer

52:10.960 --> 52:17.840
 exercising day to day control over affairs. Stalin then uses this new position to create

52:17.840 --> 52:24.480
 a personal dictatorship inside the Bolshevik dictatorship, which is the remarkable story

52:24.480 --> 52:31.840
 I tried to tell. So is there anything nefarious about any of what you just described? So it seems

52:31.840 --> 52:39.360
 conveniently that the position is created just for Stalin. There was a few other brilliant people,

52:39.360 --> 52:44.240
 arguably more brilliant than Stalin in the vicinity of Lenin. Why was Stalin chosen?

52:45.520 --> 52:54.080
 Why did Lenin all of a sudden fall ill? It's perhaps a conspiratorial question, but is there

52:54.080 --> 53:01.200
 anything nefarious about any of this historical trajectory to power that Stalin took in creating

53:01.200 --> 53:08.480
 the personal dictatorship? So history is full of contingency and surprise. After something happens,

53:09.520 --> 53:15.120
 we all think it's inevitable. It had to happen that way. Everything was leading up to it.

53:15.120 --> 53:25.440
 So Hitler seizes power in Germany in 1933, and the Nazi regime gets institutionalized by several

53:25.440 --> 53:31.760
 of his moves after being named chancellor. And so all German history becomes a story

53:31.760 --> 53:39.280
 of the Nazi rise to power, Hitler's rise to power. Every trend, tendency is bent into that

53:39.280 --> 53:46.560
 outcome. Things which don't seem related to that outcome all of a sudden get bent in that direction.

53:46.560 --> 53:52.560
 And other trends that were going on are no longer examined because they didn't lead to that outcome.

53:53.200 --> 53:59.600
 But Hitler's becoming chancellor of Germany in 1933 was not inevitable. It was contingent.

54:00.240 --> 54:05.760
 He was offered the position by the traditional conservatives. He's part of the radical right

54:05.760 --> 54:12.640
 and the traditional right named him chancellor. The Nazi party never outright won an election

54:13.280 --> 54:19.280
 that was free and fair before Hitler came to power. And in fact, its votes on the eve of

54:19.280 --> 54:25.600
 Hitler becoming chancellor declined relative to the previous election. So there's contingency in

54:25.600 --> 54:36.320
 history. And so Lenin's illness, his stroke, the neurological and blood problems that he had

54:37.120 --> 54:44.480
 were not a structure in history. In other words, if Lenin had been a healthier figure, Stalin might

54:44.480 --> 54:50.720
 never have become the Stalin that we know. That's not to say that all history is accidental,

54:50.720 --> 54:56.960
 just that we need to relate the structural, the larger structural factors to the contingent factors.

54:57.600 --> 55:03.920
 Why did Lenin pick Stalin? Well, Stalin was a very effective organizer and the position was

55:03.920 --> 55:09.760
 an organizational position. Stalin could get things done. He would carry out assignments,

55:09.760 --> 55:14.880
 no matter how difficult. He wouldn't complain that it was hard work or too much work.

55:14.880 --> 55:23.360
 He wouldn't go off womanizing and drinking and ignore his responsibilities. Lenin chose Stalin,

55:23.360 --> 55:28.320
 among other options, because he thought Stalin was the better option. Once again,

55:28.320 --> 55:32.640
 he wasn't choosing his successor because he didn't know he was going to have this stroke.

55:33.600 --> 55:39.280
 Lenin had some serious illnesses, but he had never had a major stroke before.

55:39.280 --> 55:46.800
 So, the choice was made based upon Stalin's organizational skills and promise

55:49.120 --> 55:55.520
 against the others who were in the regime. Now, they can seem more brilliant than Stalin,

55:55.520 --> 55:58.880
 but he was more effective and I'm not sure they were very brilliant.

55:59.600 --> 56:04.400
 Well, he was exceptionally competent actually at the tasks for running a government of the

56:04.400 --> 56:10.640
 executive branch of a dictator. Yes, he turned out to be very adept at being a dictator.

56:11.520 --> 56:18.480
 And so, if he had been chosen by Lenin and had not been very good, he would have been pushed

56:18.480 --> 56:26.480
 aside by others. You can get a position by accident. You can be named because you're

56:26.480 --> 56:33.440
 someone's friend or someone's relative, but to hold that position, to hold that position

56:33.440 --> 56:39.200
 in difficult circumstances, and then to build effectively a superpower on all that bloodshed.

56:40.400 --> 56:47.040
 You have to be skilled in some way. It can't be just the accident that brings you to power,

56:47.760 --> 56:54.400
 because if accident brings you to power, it won't last. Just like we discovered with Putin,

56:54.400 --> 57:01.120
 he had some qualities that we didn't foresee at the beginning, and he's been able to hold power,

57:01.120 --> 57:08.080
 not just be named. Now, Putin and Stalin are very different people. These are very different regimes.

57:08.080 --> 57:13.200
 I wouldn't put them in the same sentence. My point is not that one resembles the other.

57:14.320 --> 57:21.680
 My point is that when people come to power for contingent reasons, they don't stay in power

57:21.680 --> 57:27.840
 unless they're able to manage it. And Stalin was able to build a personal dictatorship inside

57:27.840 --> 57:35.040
 that dictatorship. He was cunning, he was ruthless, and he was a workaholic. He was very diligent.

57:35.040 --> 57:40.640
 He had a phenomenal memory, and so he could remember people's names and faces and events,

57:41.280 --> 57:48.480
 and this was very advantageous for him as he built the machine that became the Soviet state

57:48.480 --> 57:54.160
 and bureaucracy. One of the things, maybe you can correct me if I'm wrong, but you've made me

57:54.160 --> 58:02.480
 realize this wasn't some kind of manipulative personality trying to gain more power solely,

58:02.480 --> 58:11.040
 like kind of an evil picture of a person, but he truly believed in communism. As far as I can

58:11.040 --> 58:14.720
 understand, again, you can correct me if I'm wrong, but he wanted to build a better world

58:14.720 --> 58:25.360
 by having infusioned communism into the country and perhaps into the whole world.

58:26.000 --> 58:34.240
 So maybe my question is, what role does communism as an idea, as an ideology,

58:34.240 --> 58:39.920
 play in all of this, in his rise to power, in the people of the time, in the Russian people,

58:39.920 --> 58:46.160
 actually just the whole 20th century? You're right. Stalin was a true believer,

58:46.160 --> 58:50.880
 and this is very important. He was also hungry for power and for personal power,

58:51.440 --> 58:58.560
 but just as you said, not for power's sake, not only for power. He was interested in

58:58.560 --> 59:05.840
 enacting communism in reality and also in building a powerful state. He was a status,

59:05.840 --> 59:12.880
 a traditional Russian status in the imperial sense, and this won him a lot of followers.

59:13.760 --> 59:19.760
 The fact that they knew he was a hardcore true believing communist won him a lot of followers

59:19.760 --> 59:27.040
 among the communists, and the fact that he was a hardcore defender of Russian state interests

59:27.040 --> 59:33.280
 now in the Soviet guys also won him a lot of followers. Sometimes those groups overlapped

59:33.280 --> 59:39.280
 the communists and the Russian patriots, and sometimes they were completely different groups,

59:39.280 --> 59:47.680
 but both of them shared an admiration for Stalin's dedication to those goals and his abilities

59:47.680 --> 59:54.800
 to enact them. And so it's very important to understand that however thirsty he was for power,

59:54.800 --> 1:00:04.560
 and he was very thirsty for power, that he was also driven by ideals. Now, I don't necessarily

1:00:04.560 --> 1:00:13.680
 think that everyone around Stalin shared those ideals. We have to be careful not to make everybody

1:00:13.680 --> 1:00:19.360
 into a communist true believer, not to make everybody into a great status Russian patriot,

1:00:19.360 --> 1:00:29.200
 but they were widespread and powerful attractions for a lot of people. And so Stalin's ability

1:00:29.760 --> 1:00:36.240
 to communicate to people those that he was dedicated to those pursuits and his ability

1:00:36.240 --> 1:00:43.440
 to drive towards them were part of his appeal. However, he also resorted to manipulation. He

1:00:43.440 --> 1:00:51.760
 also resorted to violence. He lied. He spoke out of all sides of his mouth. He slandered other people.

1:00:51.760 --> 1:01:00.960
 He sabotaged potential rivals. He used every underhanded method and then some in order to

1:01:00.960 --> 1:01:07.120
 build his personal dictatorship. Now, he justified this, as you said, by appeals to communism

1:01:07.120 --> 1:01:15.360
 and to Soviet power to himself and to others. And so he justified it in his own mind and to others,

1:01:15.920 --> 1:01:25.920
 but certainly any means were acceptable to him to achieve these ends. And he identified his

1:01:25.920 --> 1:01:32.960
 personal power with communism and with Russian glory in the world. So he felt that he was the only

1:01:32.960 --> 1:01:40.400
 one who could be trusted, who could be relied upon to build these things. Now, we put ourselves back

1:01:40.400 --> 1:01:48.480
 in that time period. The Great Depression was a very difficult time for the capitalist system.

1:01:48.480 --> 1:01:57.680
 There was mass unemployment, a lot of hardship, fascism, Nazism, Japan, Imperial Japan.

1:01:57.680 --> 1:02:03.600
 There were a lot of associations that were negative with the kind of capitalist system

1:02:03.600 --> 1:02:14.640
 that was not 100%, not a monolith, but had a lot of authoritarian incarnations. There was imperialism,

1:02:14.640 --> 1:02:21.200
 colonies that even the democratic rule of law capital estates had non democratic,

1:02:21.200 --> 1:02:28.560
 non rule of law colonies under their rule. So the image and reality of capitalism during

1:02:28.560 --> 1:02:35.040
 that time period between World War One and World War Two was very different from how it would become

1:02:35.040 --> 1:02:42.400
 later. And so in that time period, in that interwar conjuncture after World War One before World

1:02:42.400 --> 1:02:52.160
 War Two, communism held some appeal inside the Soviet Union for sure, but even outside the Soviet

1:02:52.160 --> 1:02:57.760
 Union because the image and reality of capitalism disappointed many people. Now in the end,

1:02:57.760 --> 1:03:05.120
 communism was significantly worse. Many more victims and the system, of course, would eventually

1:03:05.120 --> 1:03:10.240
 implode. But nonetheless, there were real problems that communism tried to address.

1:03:10.240 --> 1:03:16.480
 Yes, it didn't solve those problems. It was not a solution, but it didn't come out of nowhere.

1:03:17.040 --> 1:03:25.440
 It came out of the context of that interwar period. And so Stalin's rule, some people saw it as

1:03:25.440 --> 1:03:33.280
 potentially a better option than imperialism, fascism and Great Depression. Having said that,

1:03:33.280 --> 1:03:39.280
 they were wrong. It turned out that Stalin wasn't a better alternative to markets and

1:03:39.280 --> 1:03:47.040
 private property and rule of law and democracy. However, that didn't become clearer to people

1:03:47.040 --> 1:03:54.640
 until after World War Two, after Nazism had been defeated, Imperial Japan had been defeated,

1:03:54.640 --> 1:04:00.160
 the fascist Italy had been defeated, and decolonization had happened around the world.

1:04:00.160 --> 1:04:06.720
 And there was a middle class economic boom in the period from the late 40s through the 70s

1:04:06.720 --> 1:04:13.680
 that created a kind of mass middle class in many societies. So capitalism rose from the ashes,

1:04:13.680 --> 1:04:23.440
 as it were. And this changed the game for Stalin and communism. Communism is about

1:04:23.440 --> 1:04:30.320
 an alternative to capitalism. And if that alternative is not superior, there's no reason

1:04:30.320 --> 1:04:38.400
 for communism to exist. But if capitalism is in foul odor, if people have a bad opinion,

1:04:39.520 --> 1:04:45.040
 strong critique of capitalism, there can be appeal to alternatives. And that's kind of what happened

1:04:45.040 --> 1:04:52.240
 with Stalin's rule. But after World War Two, the context changed a lot. Capitalism was very

1:04:52.240 --> 1:04:58.640
 different, much more successful, nonviolent compared to what it was in the interwar period.

1:04:58.640 --> 1:05:06.880
 And the Soviet Union had a tough time competing against that new context. Now, today, we see

1:05:06.880 --> 1:05:15.120
 similarly that the image and reality of capitalism is on the question again, which leads some people

1:05:15.120 --> 1:05:22.240
 to find an answer in socialism as an alternative. So you just kind of painted a beautiful picture

1:05:22.240 --> 1:05:29.200
 of comparison. This is the way we think about ideologies is what's working better. Do you

1:05:29.200 --> 1:05:35.440
 separate in your mind the ideals of communism to the Stalinist implementation of communism?

1:05:36.080 --> 1:05:43.520
 And again, capitalism and American implementation of capitalism. And as we look at now the 21st

1:05:43.520 --> 1:05:53.920
 century, where yes, this idea of socialism being a potential political system that we would or

1:05:53.920 --> 1:06:00.000
 economic system would operate under in the United States, rising up again as an idea. So how do we

1:06:00.000 --> 1:06:06.480
 think about that? Again, in the 21st century, about these ideas, fundamental deep ideas of

1:06:06.480 --> 1:06:13.840
 communism capitalism. Yeah. So in the Marxist schema, there was something called feudalism, which

1:06:13.840 --> 1:06:20.320
 was supposedly destroyed by the bourgeoisie who created capitalism. And then the working class

1:06:20.320 --> 1:06:26.880
 was supposed to destroy capitalism and create socialism. But socialism wasn't the end stage,

1:06:26.880 --> 1:06:32.800
 the end stage was going to be communism. So that's why the Communist Party in the Soviet Union

1:06:32.800 --> 1:06:40.560
 first built socialism, transcending capitalism. The next stage was socialism and the end game,

1:06:40.560 --> 1:06:46.480
 the final stage was communism. So their version of socialism was derived from Marx.

1:06:47.360 --> 1:06:56.160
 And Marx argued that the problem was capitalism had been very beneficial for a while.

1:06:56.160 --> 1:07:03.040
 It had produced greater wealth and greater opportunity than feudalism had. But then it had

1:07:03.040 --> 1:07:08.880
 come to serve only the narrow interests of the so called bourgeoisie or the capitalists themselves.

1:07:09.760 --> 1:07:17.280
 And so for humanity's sake, the universal class, the working class needed to overthrow capitalism

1:07:17.840 --> 1:07:24.640
 in order for greater productivity, greater wealth to be produced for all of humanity to flourish

1:07:24.640 --> 1:07:31.920
 and on a higher level. So you couldn't have socialism unless you destroyed capitalism.

1:07:31.920 --> 1:07:39.920
 So that meant no markets, no private property, no so called parliaments or bourgeois parliaments,

1:07:39.920 --> 1:07:48.320
 as they were called. So you got socialism in Marx's schema by transcending by eliminating capitalism.

1:07:48.320 --> 1:07:58.240
 Now, Marx also called for freedom. He said that this elimination of markets and private

1:07:58.240 --> 1:08:03.600
 property and bourgeois parliaments would produce greater freedom in addition to greater abundance.

1:08:04.800 --> 1:08:14.480
 However, everywhere this was tried, it produced tyranny and mass violence, death and shortages.

1:08:14.480 --> 1:08:20.880
 Everywhere it was tried. There's no exception in historical terms. And so it's very interesting.

1:08:21.920 --> 1:08:27.920
 Marx insisted that capitalism had to be eliminated. You couldn't have markets.

1:08:28.480 --> 1:08:36.000
 Markets were chaos. You needed planning. You couldn't have hiring of wage labor. That was

1:08:36.000 --> 1:08:40.800
 wage slavery. You couldn't have private property because that was a form of theft.

1:08:40.800 --> 1:08:47.520
 So in the Marxist scheme, somehow you were going to eliminate capitalism

1:08:48.560 --> 1:08:53.600
 and get to freedom. It turned out you didn't get to freedom. So then people said, well,

1:08:53.600 --> 1:08:59.520
 you can't blame Marx because he said we needed freedom. He was pro freedom.

1:09:00.400 --> 1:09:06.320
 So it's kind of like dropping a nuclear bomb. You say you're going to drop a nuclear bomb,

1:09:06.320 --> 1:09:15.680
 but you want to minimize civilian casualties. So the dropping of the nuclear bomb is the

1:09:15.680 --> 1:09:22.640
 elimination of markets, private property and parliaments. But you're going to bring freedom

1:09:22.640 --> 1:09:27.440
 or you're going to minimize civilian casualties. So you drop the nuclear bomb,

1:09:27.440 --> 1:09:37.120
 you eliminate the capitalism and you get famine, deportation, no constraints on executive power,

1:09:37.120 --> 1:09:43.760
 and not abundance, but shortages. And people say, well, that's not what Marx said. That's not what

1:09:43.760 --> 1:09:49.920
 I said. I said I wanted to minimize civilian casualties. The nuclear bomb goes off and there's

1:09:49.920 --> 1:09:57.360
 mass civilian casualties. And you keep saying, but I said drop the bomb, but minimize civilian

1:09:57.360 --> 1:10:03.360
 casualties. So that's where we are. That's history, not philosophy. I'm speaking about

1:10:03.360 --> 1:10:10.480
 historical examples, all the cases that we have. Marx was not a theorist of inequality.

1:10:11.440 --> 1:10:22.320
 Marx was a theorist of alienation, of dehumanization, of fundamental constraints or what he called

1:10:22.320 --> 1:10:28.000
 fetters on productivity and on wealth, which he all attributed to capitalism.

1:10:29.280 --> 1:10:35.040
 Marx wasn't bothered by inequality. He was bothered by something deeper, something worse.

1:10:36.720 --> 1:10:44.320
 Those socialists who figured this out, who understood that if you drop the nuclear bomb,

1:10:44.320 --> 1:10:50.400
 there was no way to minimize civilian casualties. Those socialists who came to understand

1:10:50.400 --> 1:10:56.400
 that if you eliminated capitalism, markets, private property, and parliaments, if you

1:10:56.400 --> 1:11:04.160
 eliminated that, you wouldn't get freedom. Those Marxists, those socialists became what we would

1:11:04.160 --> 1:11:10.960
 call social democrats or people who would use the state to regulate the market,

1:11:10.960 --> 1:11:18.720
 not to eliminate the market. They would use the state to redistribute income, not to destroy

1:11:18.720 --> 1:11:25.680
 private property and markets. And so this in the Marxist schema was apostasy,

1:11:26.480 --> 1:11:32.400
 because they were accepting markets and private property. They were accepting alienation and wage

1:11:32.400 --> 1:11:38.800
 slavery. They were accepting capitalism in principle, but they wanted to fix it. They wanted

1:11:38.800 --> 1:11:45.680
 to ameliorate. They wanted to regulate. And so they became what was denounced as revisionists,

1:11:45.680 --> 1:11:53.200
 not true Marxists, not real revolutionaries, but parliamentary road, parliamentarians.

1:11:54.240 --> 1:12:01.200
 We know this as normal politics, normal social democratic politics from the European case or

1:12:01.200 --> 1:12:08.800
 from the American case, but they are not asking to eliminate capitalism, blaming capitalism,

1:12:08.800 --> 1:12:16.560
 blaming markets and private property. So this rift among the socialists, the ones who are for

1:12:16.560 --> 1:12:25.680
 elimination of capitalism, transcending capitalism, otherwise you could never, ever get to abundance

1:12:25.680 --> 1:12:32.080
 and freedom in the Marxist schema versus those who accept capitalism, but want to regulate and

1:12:32.080 --> 1:12:39.920
 redistribute. That rift on the left has been with us almost from the beginning. It's a kind of civil

1:12:39.920 --> 1:12:47.200
 war on the left between the Leninists and the social democrats or the revisionists, as they're

1:12:47.200 --> 1:12:54.400
 known pejoratively by the Leninists. We have the same confusion today in the world today,

1:12:54.400 --> 1:13:04.640
 where people also cite Marx saying capitalism is a dead end, and we need to drop that nuclear bomb

1:13:04.640 --> 1:13:12.960
 and get freedom, get no civilian casualties, versus those who say, yes, there are inequities,

1:13:13.600 --> 1:13:20.560
 there's a lack of equality of opportunity. There are many other issues that we need to deal with,

1:13:20.560 --> 1:13:26.400
 and we can fix those issues, we can regulate, we can redistribute. I'm not advocating this as a

1:13:26.400 --> 1:13:32.000
 political position. I'm not taking a political position myself. I'm just saying that there's a

1:13:32.000 --> 1:13:38.800
 confusion on the left between those who accept capitalism and want to regulate it versus those

1:13:38.800 --> 1:13:43.680
 who think capitalism is inherently evil, and if we eliminate it, we'll get to a better world,

1:13:44.240 --> 1:13:49.600
 when in fact history shows that if you eliminate capitalism, you get to a worse world.

1:13:49.600 --> 1:13:53.360
 The problems might be real, but the solutions are worse.

1:13:54.320 --> 1:13:59.520
 From history's lessons, now we have deep, painful lessons, but there's not that many of them.

1:14:00.960 --> 1:14:07.920
 Our history is relatively short as a human species. Do we have a good answer on the left

1:14:07.920 --> 1:14:14.320
 of Leninists, Marxists, versus social democrat, versus capitalism, versus any

1:14:14.320 --> 1:14:23.280
 anarchy? Do we have sufficient samples from history to make better decisions about the

1:14:23.280 --> 1:14:28.240
 future of our politics and economics? For sure. We have the American Revolution,

1:14:29.040 --> 1:14:35.680
 which was a revolution not about class, not about workers, not about a so called universal

1:14:35.680 --> 1:14:40.080
 class of the working class, elimination of capitalism markets in the bourgeoisie,

1:14:40.080 --> 1:14:48.320
 but was about the category citizen. It was about universal humanity, where everyone in

1:14:48.320 --> 1:14:54.560
 theory could be part of it as a citizen. The revolution fell short of its own ideals,

1:14:55.200 --> 1:15:01.760
 not everyone was a citizen. For example, if you didn't own property, you were a male,

1:15:01.760 --> 1:15:06.960
 but didn't own property, you didn't have full rights of a citizen. If you were a female,

1:15:06.960 --> 1:15:14.400
 whether you own property or not, you weren't a full citizen. If you were imported from Africa

1:15:14.400 --> 1:15:23.360
 against your will, you were a slave and not a citizen. And so not everyone was afforded the

1:15:23.360 --> 1:15:30.560
 rights in actuality that were declared in principle. However, over time, the category

1:15:30.560 --> 1:15:36.960
 citizen could expand and slaves could be emancipated and they could get the right to vote.

1:15:36.960 --> 1:15:43.600
 They could become citizens. Non property owning males could get the right to vote and become full

1:15:43.600 --> 1:15:51.200
 citizens. Females could get the right to vote and become full citizens. In fact, eventually my

1:15:51.200 --> 1:15:57.760
 mother was able to get a credit card in her own name in the 1970s without my father having to

1:15:57.760 --> 1:16:05.760
 cosine the paperwork. It took a long time, but nonetheless, the category citizen can expand

1:16:05.760 --> 1:16:14.320
 and it can become a universal category. So we have that, the citizen universal humanity model

1:16:14.320 --> 1:16:22.000
 of the American revolution, which was deeply flawed at the time it was introduced, but fixable

1:16:22.000 --> 1:16:28.400
 over time. We also had that separation of powers and constraint on executive power that we began

1:16:28.400 --> 1:16:34.720
 this conversation with. That was also institutionalized in the American revolution because they were

1:16:34.720 --> 1:16:43.200
 afraid of tyranny. They were afraid of unconstrained executive power. So they built a system that would

1:16:43.200 --> 1:16:49.200
 contain that, constrain it institutionally, not circumstantially. So that's a great gift.

1:16:49.200 --> 1:16:57.520
 Within that universal category of citizen, which has, over time, come closer to fulfilling its

1:16:57.520 --> 1:17:03.920
 original promise, and within those institutional constraints, that separation of powers,

1:17:03.920 --> 1:17:10.160
 constraint on executive power, within that we've developed what we might call normal politics,

1:17:10.160 --> 1:17:18.960
 left, right politics. People can be in favor of redistribution and government action, and people

1:17:18.960 --> 1:17:27.360
 can be in favor of small government, hands off government, no redistribution or less redistribution.

1:17:27.840 --> 1:17:33.920
 That's the normal left, right political spectrum where you respect the institutions and separation

1:17:33.920 --> 1:17:41.200
 of powers, and you respect the universal category of citizenship and equality before the law and

1:17:41.200 --> 1:17:49.920
 everything else. I don't see any problems with that whatsoever. I see that as a great gift,

1:17:50.400 --> 1:17:55.600
 not just to this country, but around the world and other places besides the United States

1:17:55.600 --> 1:18:03.840
 have developed this. The problems arise at the extremes, the far left and the far right,

1:18:04.560 --> 1:18:11.120
 that don't recognize the legitimacy either of capitalism or of democratic rule of law

1:18:11.120 --> 1:18:17.360
 institutions, and they want to eliminate constraints on executive power. They want to control the

1:18:17.360 --> 1:18:24.080
 public sphere or diminish the independence of the media. They want to take away markets or

1:18:24.080 --> 1:18:29.440
 private property, and redistribution becomes something bigger than just redistribution. It

1:18:29.440 --> 1:18:38.160
 becomes actually that original Marxist idea of transcending capitalism. I'm not bothered by the

1:18:38.160 --> 1:18:44.800
 left or the right. I think they're normal, and we should have that debate. We're a gigantic,

1:18:44.800 --> 1:18:52.400
 diverse country of many different political points of view. I'm troubled only by the extremes

1:18:52.400 --> 1:18:59.280
 that are against the system, cross system, that want to get rid of it, and supposedly that will be

1:18:59.840 --> 1:19:05.440
 the right path to the future. History tells us that the far left and the far right are wrong

1:19:05.440 --> 1:19:12.640
 about that. But once again, this doesn't mean that you have to be a social democrat. You could be a

1:19:12.640 --> 1:19:20.000
 libertarian. You could be a conservative. You could be a centrist. You could be conservative on some

1:19:20.000 --> 1:19:25.520
 issues and liberal on other issues. All of that comes under what I would presume to be normal

1:19:25.520 --> 1:19:32.640
 politics. And I see that as the important corrective mechanism, normal politics and market economies,

1:19:33.440 --> 1:19:41.040
 non monopolistic, open, free, and dynamic market economies. I don't like concentrations of power

1:19:41.040 --> 1:19:47.600
 politically, and I don't like concentrations of power economically. I like competition in the

1:19:47.600 --> 1:19:56.000
 political realm. I like competition in the economic realm. This is not perfect. It constantly

1:19:57.200 --> 1:20:05.200
 needs to be protected and reinvented. There are flaws that are fundamental and need to be adjusted

1:20:05.200 --> 1:20:11.920
 and addressed and everything else, especially equality of opportunity. Equality of outcome

1:20:11.920 --> 1:20:20.240
 is unreachable and is a mistake because it produces perverse and unintended consequences,

1:20:20.240 --> 1:20:26.480
 equality of outcome attempts, attempts to make people equal on the outcome side,

1:20:27.200 --> 1:20:33.440
 but attempts to make them more equal on the front end, on the opportunity side. That's really,

1:20:33.440 --> 1:20:40.320
 really important for a healthy society. That's where we've fallen down. Our schools are not

1:20:40.320 --> 1:20:48.320
 providing equality of opportunity for the majority of people in all of our school systems.

1:20:48.960 --> 1:20:57.360
 And so I see problems there. I see a need to invest in ourselves, invest in infrastructure,

1:20:57.360 --> 1:21:04.160
 invest in human capital, create greater equality of opportunity, but also to make sure that we

1:21:04.160 --> 1:21:10.000
 have good governance because governance is the variable that enables you to do all these other

1:21:10.000 --> 1:21:16.160
 things. I've watched quite a bit returning back to Putin. I've watched quite a few interviews

1:21:16.960 --> 1:21:23.120
 with Putin and conversations, especially because I speak Russian fluently. I can

1:21:23.120 --> 1:21:37.920
 understand often the translations lose a lot. I find the man putting morality aside very deep

